  "prompt": "Why does blue vitriol change its colour from blue to white on heating?",
  "response": "Blue vitriol is the common name for copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate (CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O), which is characterized by its vibrant blue crystals. The blue color arises from the presence of water molecules coordinated to the copper(II) ions in the crystal structure. Here's what happens when blue vitriol is heated:\n\n1. **Dehydration (Loss of Water of Crystallization):**\n   - **Structure Before Heating:** In CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O, each copper ion is surrounded by water molecules. These water molecules influence the electronic environment of the copper ions, leading to specific absorption of light in the visible spectrum that imparts the blue color.\n   - **Heating Process:** When blue vitriol is heated, it undergoes dehydration, meaning it loses its water molecules. Specifically, it loses the five water molecules bound to each copper ion.\n\n2. **Change in Coordination and Electronic Structure:**\n   - **Anhydrous Copper(II) Sulfate:** Upon losing the water molecules, the compound becomes anhydrous copper(II) sulfate (CuSO\u2084). Without the water molecules coordinating to the copper ions, the crystal field around the copper changes.\n   - **Color Change Mechanism:** The absence of water alters the d-orbital splitting in copper ions, affecting how they absorb and reflect light. Without the water ligands, the complex no longer has the same electronic transitions that produce the blue color.\n\n3. **Resulting Appearance:**\n   - **White Color:** Anhydrous copper(II) sulfate appears as white or grayish-white crystals, a stark contrast to the bright blue of its hydrated form. This colorless appearance is due to the lack of coordinated water molecules that were responsible for the blue coloration.\n\n**Chemical Equation for Dehydration:**\n\\[ \\text{CuSO}_4 \\cdot 5\\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\xrightarrow{\\text{heat}} \\text{CuSO}_4 + 5\\text{H}_2\\text{O} \\]\n\n**Summary:**\nThe transition from blue to white upon heating blue vitriol is primarily due to the loss of water molecules that were coordinated to the copper ions. This dehydration alters the electronic environment of copper, changing the way it interacts with light and thus its observable color.",
